I have proposed a refinement to the "longer runs are more random" hypothesis by incorporating a non-linear perceptual scaling step (Stevens' Power Law).

The hypothesis (`hypothesis.md`) and the PyMC model (`candidate.py`) have been correctly implemented and verify against PyMC parsing checks. The model scales the linearly normalized maximum run length by a learned power (`gamma`) before comparing them through the standard logistic function, enabling it to fit diminishing or accelerating returns for streak lengths without blending in any new cues.
